Tshwane mayor Stevens Mokgalapa's future continues to hang in the balance. Courtesy #DStv403 PRETORIA - Tshwane mayor Stevens Mokgalapa's future continues to hang in the balance. The DA's Gauteng leader John Moodey says parallel processes are underway within the city council and the party to determine Mokgalapa's fitness for office. Mokgalapa had been placed on special leave over a sex scandal at work. READ: DA going to court over Mokgalapa's removal as Tshwane mayor Moodey said Mokgalapa's future will be decided soon. "The federal legal council has concluded its investigations and it will be tabled in two weeks time, so we'll deal with that then," said Moodey. In early December last year, MEC for Human Settlements and Cooperative Governance Lebogang Maile said he was planning to place Tshwane under administration. READ: Tshwane leadership battle delayed The ANC in Tshwane says it's not business as usual in the capital city and its pushing to remove all of the DA's presiding officers this week. Despite this, acting mayor Abel Tau says the city's leaders are hard at work to deliver services and don't plan to be sidetracked by opposition efforts to unseat them.